        '```html\n<article>\n    <section>\n        <h2>Brief Introduction</h2>\n        <p>René Descartes (1596 – 1650) was a highly influential French philosopher, mathematician, and scientist.  A key figure in the 17th-century intellectual revolution, he is often considered the father of modern Western philosophy.  His work, characterized by a focus on reason and systematic doubt, laid the groundwork for many subsequent philosophical and scientific developments.</p>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h2>Early Life and Background</h2>\n        <p>Born in La Haye en Touraine (now Descartes), France, René Descartes was from a family of minor nobility. He received a classical education at the Jesuit college of La Flèche, where he studied philosophy, logic, and mathematics.  Dissatisfied with the traditional Aristotelian scholasticism taught there, Descartes embarked on a period of travel and military service, during which he increasingly focused on his own philosophical investigations.</p>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h2>Main Philosophical Contributions</h2>\n        <p>Descartes is primarily associated with the philosophical school of <b>Rationalism</b>, which emphasizes the role of reason as the primary source of knowledge.  He is also considered the founder of <b>Cartesianism</b>, a school of thought based on his specific doctrines.  Descartes\'s philosophical approach also embraced <b>Mechanism</b>, the idea that the natural world operates like a machine according to mechanical principles.  His early philosophical views were influenced by <b>Augustinianism</b>, and he is significant in the development of <b>Foundationalism</b>, the idea that knowledge is built on a secure base of fundamental principles.</p>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h2>Key Ideas and Concepts</h2>\n        <p>Descartes is renowned for several key ideas:</p>\n        \n        <h3>The Cogito Argument</h3>\n        <p>Perhaps his most famous concept is expressed in the phrase "<b>I think, therefore I am</b>" ("<i>Cogito, ergo sum</i>"). This idea, reached through radical doubt, posits that the very act of doubting proves the existence of a thinking subject.</p>\n        \n        <h3>Methodological Doubt</h3>\n        <p>Descartes advocated a rigorous method of inquiry based on systematically doubting all beliefs until one reaches an indubitable certainty, from which other knowledge can be deduced.  This is encapsulated in his idea: "<b>If you would be a real seeker after truth, it is necessary that at least once in your life you doubt, as far as possible, all things.</b>"</p>\n        \n        <h3>The Importance of Reason</h3>\n       <p>Descartes emphasized the need for proper use of reason, stating:  "<b>It is not enough to have a good mind; the main thing is to use it well.</b>" He believed clear and distinct ideas are a sign of their truth.</p>\n\n        <h3>Rules for Problem Solving</h3>\n        <p>He proposed a set of rules for approaching problems, including: "<b>Divide each difficulty into as many parts as is feasible and necessary to resolve it.</b>" He also noted that: "<b>Each problem that I solved became a rule, which served afterwards to solve other problems.</b>"</p>\n\n        <h3>Human Nature</h3>\n         <p>Descartes expressed complexities of human nature with his assertion that:  "<b>The greatest minds are capable of the greatest vices as well as of the greatest virtues.</b>"  He also commented on the limitations of human control: "<b>Except our own thoughts, there is nothing absolutely in our power</b>" and on the need to use probabilities when certainty is unattainable: "<b>When it is not in our power to follow what is true, we ought to follow what is most probable.</b>" He also expressed rareties saying that: "<b>Perfect numbers like perfect men are very rare.</b>"</p>\n\n        <h3>The Nature of Knowledge</h3>\n        <p>Descartes suggested that: "<b>Everything is self-evident,</b>" although this is interpreted within his framework of systematic doubt and the search for fundamental truths. He also emphasized that: "<b>The reading of all good books is like a conversation with the finest minds of past centuries.</b>"</p>\n        \n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h2>Major Works</h2>\n        <p>Descartes\'s most influential philosophical work is his <b>Discourse on the Method of Rightly Conducting One\'s Reason and of Seeking Truth in the Sciences</b> (1637).  This text outlines his methodological principles and also includes essays on optics, geometry, and meteorology.</p>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h2>Influence and Legacy</h2>\n        <p>Descartes\'s impact on philosophy and science is immense.  His emphasis on reason and individual thought helped usher in the Enlightenment era.  His analytic geometry, a fusion of algebra and geometry, revolutionized mathematics.  His systematic doubt and his focus on the self as the starting point for knowledge are cornerstones of modern philosophy. He is also a key influence on the field of epistemology, specifically with his emphasis on foundationalism and justification of knowledge.  Despite some criticisms and adaptations of his ideas over time, his legacy continues to shape philosophical and scientific inquiry.</p>\n    </section>\n</article>\n```\n',
