        '```html\n<section>\n  <h2>Immanuel Kant</h2>\n  <p>Immanuel Kant (1724-1804) was a German philosopher and one of the central Enlightenment thinkers. His comprehensive and systematic work in epistemology, ethics, and aesthetics influenced all subsequent philosophy. Kant is considered one of the most important figures in the history of Western philosophy.</p>\n</section>\n\n<section>\n  <h2>Early Life and Background</h2>\n  <p>Born in Königsberg, Prussia (now Kaliningrad, Russia), Kant spent his entire life in and around his hometown.  He was raised in a Pietist household, which emphasized religious devotion and moral integrity. He attended the Collegium Fridericianum and the University of Königsberg, studying philosophy, mathematics, and physics. Although he lectured on a variety of subjects for many years, he did not become a full professor until 1770. </p>\n</section>\n\n<section>\n  <h2>Main Philosophical Contributions</h2>\n  <p>Kant’s philosophical contributions are vast and encompass various fields, including metaphysics, epistemology, ethics, aesthetics, and politics. He is best known for his transcendental idealism, which argues that our experience is structured by the mind’s own categories and forms, and for his deontological moral philosophy centered on the categorical imperative.</p>\n</section>\n\n<section>\n  <h2>Key Ideas and Concepts</h2>\n    <p>Kant\'s work is characterized by several recurring ideas and concepts:</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Transcendental Idealism:</strong> This philosophical position asserts that the human mind plays an active role in structuring our experience of reality. We do not perceive the world as it is in itself (the noumenal realm), but as it appears to us (the phenomenal realm) through our forms of intuition (space and time) and categories of the understanding.</li>\n    <li><strong>The Categorical Imperative:</strong> A central concept in Kant\'s moral philosophy, the categorical imperative is an unconditional moral law that dictates our actions should be universalizable (that is, applicable to everyone) and treat people as ends in themselves, not merely as means to an end.</li>\n    <li><strong>The Synthesis of Rationalism and Empiricism:</strong> Kant sought to reconcile the two opposing schools of thought: rationalism (which emphasized reason as the source of knowledge) and empiricism (which emphasized experience). He argued that both reason and experience are necessary for knowledge.</li>\n  </ul>\n    <p>Kant expressed various other insightful ideas, including:</p>\n    <ul>\n         <li>“He who is cruel to animals becomes hard also in his dealings with men. We can judge the heart of a man by his treatment of animals.”</li>\n         <li>“Happiness is not an ideal of reason, but of imagination.”</li>\n        <li> “Science is organized knowledge. Wisdom is organized life.”</li>\n        <li> “Live your life as though your every act were to become a universal law.”</li>\n        <li>“Thoughts without content are empty, intuitions without concepts are blind.”</li>\n        <li> “Give me matter, and I will construct a world out of it!”</li>\n        <li> “Experience without theory is blind, but theory without experience is mere intellectual play.”</li>\n       <li>  “Ingratitude is the essence of vileness.”</li>\n        <li> “I had therefore to remove knowledge, in order to make room for belief.”</li>\n        <li>  “What can I know? What ought I to do? What can I hope?”</li>\n        <li>  “We are not rich by what we possess but by what we can do without.”</li>\n       <li> “How then is perfection to be sought? Wherein lies our hope? In education, and in nothing else.”</li>\n         <li>“All our knowledge begins with the senses, proceeds then to the understanding, and ends with reason. There is nothing higher than reason.”</li>\n        <li>  “There is something splendid about innocence; but what is bad about it, in turn, is that it cannot protect itself very well and is easily seduced.”</li>\n        <li> “One who makes himself a worm cannot complain afterwards if people step on him.”</li>\n         <li>“The busier we are, the more acutely we feel that we live, the more conscious we are of life.”</li>\n         <li>"Genius is the ability to independently arrive at and understand concepts that would normally have to be taught by another person."</li>\n        <li>“Man must be disciplined, for he is by nature raw and wild…”</li>\n        <li>“An action, to have moral worth, must be done from duty.”</li>\n        <li>“Whereas the beautiful is limited, the sublime is limitless, so that the mind in the presence of the sublime, attempting to imagine what it cannot, has pain in the failure but pleasure in contemplating the immensity of the attempt.”</li>\n       <li> “Morality is not properly the doctrine of how we may make ourselves happy, but how we may make ourselves worthy of happiness.”</li>\n        <li>“For peace to reign on Earth, humans must evolve into new beings who have learned to see the whole first, Only he who, himself enlightened, is not afraid of shadows.”</li>\n       <li> "Space and time are the framework within which the mind is constrained to construct its experience of reality."</li>\n      <li>“Enlightenment is man’s emergence from his self-imposed immaturity. Immaturity is the inability to use one’s understanding without guidance from another.”</li>\n        <li>"By a lie a man throws away and as it were annihilates his dignity as a man."</li>\n    </ul>\n</section>\n\n<section>\n  <h2>Major Works</h2>\n  <p>Kant produced several influential works, including:</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><em>Critique of Pure Reason</em> (1781, 1787) - Explores the limits and scope of human reason.</li>\n    <li><em>Critique of Practical Reason</em> (1788) - Focuses on moral philosophy and the categorical imperative.</li>\n    <li><em>Critique of Judgment</em> (1790) - Deals with aesthetics and teleology.</li>\n    <li><em>Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals</em> (1785) - Provides a systematic account of Kantian ethics.</li>\n    <li><em>Perpetual Peace: A Philosophical Sketch</em> (1795) - Outlines his vision for international relations and peace.</li>\n  </ul>\n</section>\n\n<section>\n  <h2>Influence and Legacy</h2>\n  <p>Kant\'s philosophy has had a profound and lasting impact on Western thought. His work revolutionized epistemology and ethics, and his ideas continue to be debated and studied. He founded the schools of Kantianism, Transcendental Idealism, and is considered an influence of Classical Liberalism. His influence can be seen in various fields, including philosophy, law, politics, and even art. Kant\'s emphasis on reason, autonomy, and the dignity of the human being remains a vital part of modern intellectual discourse. </p>\n</section>\n```\n',
