      content:
        '```html\n<article>\n    <section>\n        <h2>Overview and Definition</h2>\n        <p>Kantianism is a philosophical system developed by the 18th-century German philosopher Immanuel Kant. It is primarily concerned with epistemology, ethics, and aesthetics, and is characterized by its emphasis on reason, autonomy, and the inherent moral worth of individuals. Kantianism seeks to establish universal principles that can guide human action and understanding. At its core, it proposes that our knowledge of the world is shaped not only by sensory experience but also by the inherent structures of our minds.  In ethics, it posits that moral obligation stems from reason itself, not from consequences or emotions.</p>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h2>Historical Development</h2>\n        <p>Kantianism arose in the context of the Enlightenment, responding to both the rationalist and empiricist traditions. While rationalists like Descartes believed that knowledge was primarily derived from innate ideas, and empiricists like Locke emphasized the importance of sensory experience, Kant argued that both were necessary. He termed his own approach "transcendental idealism" to reflect the idea that our understanding of reality is structured by a priori (pre-experiential) categories of thought. Kant\'s pivotal work, "Critique of Pure Reason" (1781), laid the groundwork for his system. He further developed his ethical theories in "Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals" (1785) and "Critique of Practical Reason" (1788), and his aesthetics in "Critique of Judgement" (1790). </p>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h2>Key Principles and Concepts</h2>\n        <section>\n            <h3>Epistemology</h3>\n            <p>A central concept in Kantian epistemology is the distinction between "phenomena" (the world as it appears to us) and "noumena" (the world as it is in itself, independent of our perception). Kant argued that we can only know phenomena, which are shaped by our innate categories of understanding (such as space, time, and causality). These categories are the conditions for the possibility of our experience. Another key concept is the "synthetic a priori" judgment, which is both informative about the world (synthetic) and knowable through reason alone (a priori).</p>\n        </section>\n         <section>\n            <h3>Ethics</h3>\n             <p>Kantian ethics is deontological, meaning that it emphasizes duty and rules rather than consequences. Central to Kant\'s ethical thought is the concept of the "categorical imperative," which is a universal moral law that all rational beings are bound to follow. Kant formulated this imperative in several ways, including the Formula of Universal Law ("Act only according to that maxim whereby you can at the same time will that it should become a universal law") and the Formula of Humanity ("Act in such a way that you treat humanity, whether in your own person or in the person of any other, never merely as a means to an end, but always at the same time as an end"). Kant also stresses the importance of the "good will," which is the will motivated by duty, and the concept of autonomy, which refers to our ability to give ourselves moral law.</p>\n         </section>\n        <section>\n            <h3>Aesthetics</h3>\n            <p>Kantian aesthetics focuses on the nature of beauty and aesthetic judgment. Kant argued that aesthetic judgments are disinterested, universal, and necessary. He distinguished between the beautiful (which is pleasing in its form) and the sublime (which overwhelms us with its grandeur). He also argued that aesthetic judgment is grounded in a subjective but universal feeling that arises from the harmonious interplay of our cognitive faculties.</p>\n        </section>\n    </section>\n    <section>\n         <h2>Major Figures and Contributors</h2>\n         <h3>Immanuel Kant (1724-1804)</h3>\n         <p>Immanuel Kant is undeniably the central figure in Kantianism. His works laid the foundation for the entire philosophical system.  While there are subsequent interpretations, all are rooted in his seminal writings. He is known for his rigorous and systematic approach to philosophy, influencing virtually every subsequent field of philosophical inquiry.</p>\n        <p>While Kant remains the primary contributor, other figures have developed and modified Kantian ideas. These include: </p>\n         <ul>\n           <li><strong>Neo-Kantians:</strong> A movement in late 19th and early 20th centuries that sought to revive and reinterpret Kant\'s philosophy. Key figures include Hermann Cohen and Paul Natorp.</li>\n           <li><strong>Contemporary Kantians:</strong> Contemporary philosophers continue to engage with and build upon Kantian ideas, applying them to new ethical and political challenges. Notable figures include John Rawls, Onora O\'Neill and Christine Korsgaard.</li>\n         </ul>\n    </section>\n    <section>\n        <h2>Influence and Modern Relevance</h2>\n        <p>Kantianism has had a profound influence on Western philosophy, and its ideas continue to be debated and developed. Its emphasis on reason, autonomy, and universal moral principles has been particularly influential in ethics and political philosophy, providing a theoretical framework for discussions about human rights, justice, and democracy. In the realm of epistemology, Kantianism\'s emphasis on the structure of the mind and the limitations of our knowledge has shaped the way we understand science and cognition.  Furthermore, his concepts of the categorical imperative and treating people as ends in themselves remain foundational to many ethical frameworks today. His work continues to spark vigorous debate and remains a central point of reference in philosophical discussions.</p>\n    </section>\n</article>\n```\n',
