      content:
        '```html\n<section>\n    <h2>Classical Liberalism and Immanuel Kant</h2>\n\n    <section>\n        <h3>Overview and Definition</h3>\n        <p>Classical liberalism is a political ideology and a branch of liberalism that advocates for civil liberties and political freedom with an emphasis on limited government under the rule of law, economic freedom, and individual autonomy.  It emerged as a distinct political movement in the late 18th and early 19th centuries, building upon earlier enlightenment thought. Unlike later forms of liberalism, classical liberalism often emphasized a more laissez-faire approach to economic policy and focused on negative liberties, such as freedom from governmental interference.</p>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h3>Historical Development</h3>\n        <p>The roots of classical liberalism can be traced back to the Enlightenment period and the writings of philosophers such as John Locke, who emphasized natural rights and limited government. The Glorious Revolution in England and the American Revolution were significant events that helped to shape the political and philosophical landscape in which classical liberalism developed.  The ideas gained momentum during the 18th century, influencing revolutions and the development of constitutional governments in several countries. The 19th century saw its peak influence, driving movements for free trade, parliamentary reform, and the abolition of slavery.</p>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h3>Key Principles and Concepts</h3>\n        <p>Central to classical liberalism are several key principles:</p>\n        <ul>\n            <li><strong>Individual Liberty:</strong> The belief that individuals possess inherent rights to freedom of thought, speech, association, and property.</li>\n            <li><strong>Limited Government:</strong>  A conviction that government should have restricted powers, primarily concerned with protecting individual rights and enforcing contracts.</li>\n             <li><strong>Rule of Law:</strong> The principle that everyone, including those in government, are subject to the law and that the law should be applied equally.</li>\n            <li><strong>Free Markets:</strong>  Advocacy for a system with minimal government intervention in the economy, promoting competition and individual economic choice.</li>\n             <li><strong>Private Property:</strong> The protection of private property rights as fundamental to both individual freedom and economic prosperity.</li>\n             <li><strong>Civil Liberties:</strong> An emphasis on freedoms such as freedom of speech, freedom of assembly, and freedom of religion.</li>\n        </ul>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h3>Major Figures and Contributors</h3>\n        <p>Classical liberalism\'s development was shaped by a diverse array of thinkers. Key figures include:</p>\n        <ul>\n            <li><strong>John Locke:</strong> Often considered the father of classical liberalism, his ideas on natural rights and limited government greatly influenced the movement.</li>\n            <li><strong>Adam Smith:</strong> His work "The Wealth of Nations" provided the economic framework for classical liberalism by promoting free markets.</li>\n            <li><strong>Montesquieu:</strong> Advocated for the separation of powers within government as a way to prevent tyranny.</li>\n            <li><strong>David Ricardo:</strong> Developed economic theories, such as comparative advantage, that supported free trade.</li>\n            <li><strong>Immanuel Kant:</strong> Although not exclusively a classical liberal, his emphasis on individual autonomy, universal moral laws, and the importance of reason contributed significantly to the philosophical underpinnings of the movement. Kant\'s emphasis on duty and his categorical imperative had considerable influence on thinking about individual rights and obligations. He supported the idea of a state based on the rule of law that would secure civil rights and freedom of thought, thus aligning with key classical liberal values. </li>\n            <li><strong>John Stuart Mill:</strong>  A later classical liberal who emphasized individual liberty and utilitarianism, arguing for freedom of thought and expression as essential for progress.</li>\n        </ul>\n    </section>\n\n    <section>\n        <h3>Influence and Modern Relevance</h3>\n         <p>Classical liberalism profoundly influenced the development of modern democratic societies and capitalist economies.  Its principles helped to shape constitutions and legal systems around the world. While its dominance waned in the 20th century with the rise of social liberalism and other ideologies, classical liberal ideas continue to be influential in contemporary political discourse. They are often invoked in discussions on free markets, limited government, and individual liberties, and inform many modern libertarian perspectives.</p>\n    </section>\n\n</section>\n```\n',
