    english: {
      title: 'Cartesianism',
      content:
        '```html\n<article>\n    <section>\n        <h2>Overview and Definition</h2>\n        <p>Cartesianism, named after its founder René Descartes, is a philosophical and scientific system that dominated Western thought during the 17th and 18th centuries. At its core, Cartesianism is characterized by a method of inquiry rooted in radical doubt and a dualistic metaphysics that sharply separates mind and matter. It emphasizes reason, deduction, and the existence of innate ideas as fundamental to knowledge acquisition.  The term encompasses not only Descartes\' own views, but also the interpretations and developments of his philosophy by his followers and critics.</p>\n    </section>\n    <section>\n        <h2>Historical Development</h2>\n        <p>Cartesianism emerged in the context of the scientific revolution and the decline of Aristotelian scholasticism. Descartes, seeking a secure foundation for knowledge, published his foundational works, including <em>Discourse on the Method</em> (1637) and <em>Meditations on First Philosophy</em> (1641), which articulated his methodical doubt and dualistic philosophy.  His ideas quickly gained traction and sparked both fervent support and intense opposition, leading to a period of vibrant philosophical and scientific debate across Europe. The spread of his ideas was facilitated by his published works and his extensive correspondence with other thinkers.</p>\n        <p>While many of Descartes\' specific scientific theories were later superseded, his methodical skepticism and the emphasis on rational deduction heavily influenced the development of modern science, and the separation of mind and matter has continued to shape philosophical discourse.</p>\n    </section>\n    <section>\n        <h2>Key Principles and Concepts</h2>\n        <p>Several key principles and concepts define Cartesianism:</p>\n        <h3>Methodical Doubt</h3>\n        <p>Descartes advocated a method of systematic doubt, questioning all previously held beliefs to discover a foundation of indubitable knowledge. This led him to the famous "Cogito, ergo sum" ("I think, therefore I am"), which he considered the first undeniable truth.</p>\n        <h3>Substance Dualism</h3>\n        <p>Central to Cartesianism is the concept of substance dualism, which posits that reality consists of two distinct and fundamentally different substances: mind (res cogitans), characterized by thought and consciousness, and matter (res extensa), defined by its extension in space. Descartes argued that these substances are completely separate and do not require each other for their existence.</p>\n        <h3>Innate Ideas</h3>\n        <p>Descartes maintained that certain ideas, such as the idea of God, perfection, and mathematical truths, are not derived from experience but are innate or implanted in the mind by God. These innate ideas serve as a priori foundations for knowledge.</p>\n        <h3>Mechanism</h3>\n        <p>In regards to the material world, Cartesianism embraced a mechanistic worldview. Descartes viewed the physical universe, including the human body, as a complex machine governed by mechanical laws. This concept significantly influenced the development of physics and biology.</p>\n        <h3>Rationalism</h3>\n        <p>Cartesianism is a key example of rationalism, an epistemological position that emphasizes reason and innate ideas as the primary sources of knowledge, rather than sensory experience. This contrasted with empiricism, which prioritizes sensory observation.</p>\n    </section>\n    <section>\n        <h2>Major Figures and Contributors</h2>\n        <h3>René Descartes</h3>\n         <p>The central figure of Cartesianism, René Descartes (1596-1650), a French philosopher, mathematician, and scientist,  developed the foundational concepts and principles of the system. His works like <em>Discourse on the Method</em>, <em>Meditations on First Philosophy</em>, and <em>Principles of Philosophy</em> are essential texts for understanding Cartesian thought.</p>\n        <h3>Nicolas Malebranche</h3>\n        <p>A French Oratorian priest and philosopher (1638-1715), Malebranche was a prominent follower of Descartes who developed Occasionalism, the theory that God is the only true causal agent, and created a way to explain mind-body interaction. While diverging from Descartes on some points, he extended and clarified many Cartesian doctrines.</p>\n        <h3>Antoine Arnauld</h3>\n        <p>A French theologian and philosopher (1612-1694), Arnauld was a significant critic of Cartesianism, primarily engaging with its theological implications and with his own rationalist views. He questioned some of Descartes\' fundamental claims and helped to refine the discourse surrounding them.</p>\n\n    </section>\n    <section>\n        <h2>Influence and Modern Relevance</h2>\n        <p>Cartesianism has had a profound and lasting influence on Western philosophy, science, and culture. Its emphasis on rationalism and methodical inquiry helped to establish the framework for modern science. The concept of the separation between mind and matter continues to be a central topic in philosophy of mind, cognitive science, and artificial intelligence. Even today, despite much criticism and revision, Cartesian ideas inform the discussion around consciousness, personhood, and the nature of reality. The legacy of Cartesianism extends beyond the confines of philosophy, influencing fields as diverse as mathematics, physics, psychology, and computer science.  The notion of a thinking, subjective self, distinct from the objective material world, remains a cornerstone of modern Western thought, thanks to the impact of Cartesianism.</p>\n    </section>\n</article>\n```\n',
    },
