      content:
        '```html\n<section>\n    <h2>Continental Philosophy</h2>\n    <section>\n        <h3>Overview and Definition</h3>\n        <p>Continental philosophy is a term used to describe a set of philosophical traditions originating in 19th and 20th-century Europe. Unlike analytic philosophy, which is dominant in the English-speaking world, continental philosophy tends to be more concerned with broader cultural and historical contexts, often engaging with themes of subjectivity, existentialism, hermeneutics, and the nature of power. It is characterized by a rejection of scientism and a preference for qualitative over quantitative methods of inquiry.  The boundaries of what constitutes continental philosophy are fluid and debated, but it is generally understood as encompassing a range of diverse movements that often overlap and interact with each other.</p>\n    </section>\n    <section>\n        <h3>Historical Development</h3>\n        <p>The origins of continental philosophy are often traced back to the aftermath of Immanuel Kant\'s critical philosophy and the rise of German Idealism.  Figures like Johann Gottlieb Fichte and Friedrich Schelling grappled with Kant\'s transcendental idealism, paving the way for the development of more historically-conscious philosophical systems.  A crucial moment was the work of Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel, whose dialectical method and philosophy of history exerted a profound influence on later thinkers. The mid-19th century saw a reaction against Hegelianism, with thinkers like Søren Kierkegaard and Arthur Schopenhauer offering alternatives focusing on individual existence and the irrational aspects of reality. In the 20th century, the phenomenological movement, associated with Edmund Husserl and later Martin Heidegger, became central to many branches of continental thought. The rise of post-structuralism and postmodernism from figures like Jacques Derrida and Michel Foucault further expanded the scope of continental philosophy and its critiques of established power structures and traditional modes of thought.</p>\n    </section>\n    <section>\n        <h3>Key Principles and Concepts</h3>\n        <p>Several key principles and concepts are frequently explored within continental philosophy. These include:</p>\n        <ul>\n            <li><strong>Historicity:</strong> A strong emphasis on the historical context of ideas and their development. Philosophical inquiry is seen as inherently situated within a particular time and place.</li>\n            <li><strong>Subjectivity:</strong> A focus on individual experience and perspectives, often challenging the notion of an objective, universal truth.</li>\n            <li><strong>Existentialism:</strong> A concern with the nature of human existence, freedom, responsibility, and the experience of meaninglessness.</li>\n            <li><strong>Hermeneutics:</strong> The theory and practice of interpretation, emphasizing the role of understanding and meaning-making in human thought and action.</li>\n            <li><strong>Critique of Power:</strong> An investigation into the ways in which power operates and shapes social, political, and cultural relations.</li>\n            <li><strong>Phenomenology:</strong> An approach focused on describing the lived experience of consciousness, often through reflection on its intentionality and the appearance of phenomena.</li>\n            <li><strong>Rejection of Metanarratives:</strong>  A skepticism towards overarching theories and explanations that claim to be universally valid.</li>\n        </ul>\n    </section>\n    <section>\n        <h3>Major Figures and Contributors</h3>\n        <p>Several philosophers have been particularly influential in the development and shaping of continental thought. Among them are:</p>\n        <ul>\n            <li><strong>Arthur Schopenhauer (1788-1860):</strong> Known for his pessimistic philosophy centered on the concept of "will" as a blind and irrational force driving all of existence. His work had a profound impact on figures like Friedrich Nietzsche and Sigmund Freud.</li>\n            <li><strong>Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel (1770-1831):</strong> A pivotal figure of German Idealism, whose philosophy emphasized the dialectical process and the role of history in shaping thought and society. His ideas laid the groundwork for both Marxism and existentialism.</li>\n            <li><strong>Søren Aabye Kierkegaard (1813-1855):</strong> A Danish philosopher considered the father of existentialism, who focused on the nature of individual existence, subjective truth, and the tension between faith and reason.</li>\n            <li><strong>Martin Heidegger (1889-1976):</strong> A key figure of phenomenology and existentialism, known for his analysis of "being" and his influential concept of "Dasein" (being-there).  His work has had lasting effects on philosophy, theology, and literary theory.</li>\n        </ul>\n    </section>\n    <section>\n        <h3>Influence and Modern Relevance</h3>\n        <p>Continental philosophy has had a significant influence on various fields beyond philosophy, including literary criticism, sociology, political theory, psychology, and art history. Its insights into the nature of language, power, subjectivity, and interpretation continue to be relevant in contemporary debates.  The focus on issues of social justice, identity, and the critique of established norms have made continental thought crucial for understanding the complex challenges of the 21st century. While often viewed as distinct from the analytic tradition, the insights of continental philosophy offer important perspectives and methodologies for enriching philosophical discourse and understanding the human condition in its historical and cultural context.</p>\n    </section>\n</section>\n```\n',
